<div class="tab-content active" id="notes-2-2">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>This section is pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">The Law of Supply</h2>
    <p>The <strong>law of supply</strong> states that, ceteris paribus, as the price of a good rises, the quantity supplied rises; as price falls, quantity supplied falls. There is a <strong>positive (direct) relationship</strong> between price and quantity supplied.</p>
    <p>The supply curve slopes <strong>upward</strong> from left to right. Higher prices make production more profitable, incentivising producers to supply more.</p>

    <div class="callout key-term">
      <div class="callout-title">Key term</div>
      <p><strong>Supply:</strong> The quantity of a good or service that producers are willing and able to offer for sale at various prices during a given time period, ceteris paribus.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout hl-only">
      <div class="callout-title">HL only — Underlying assumptions</div>
      <p><strong>Law of diminishing marginal returns:</strong> As more of a variable factor (e.g., labour) is added to fixed factors (e.g., land, capital), each additional unit eventually adds less and less to output. This means output increases at a decreasing rate.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:0.5rem;"><strong>Increasing marginal costs:</strong> Because of diminishing returns, producing each additional unit costs more than the last. Firms therefore need higher prices to justify producing more — hence the upward-sloping supply curve.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Individual vs Market Supply</h2>
    <p>The <strong>individual supply curve</strong> shows how much one firm offers at each price. The <strong>market supply curve</strong> is the horizontal summation of all individual supply curves.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Non-Price Determinants of Supply</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Determinant</th><th>Shift right (increase in supply)</th><th>Shift left (decrease in supply)</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Costs of factors of production</strong></td><td>Factor costs fall (e.g., wages, raw materials)</td><td>Factor costs rise</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Technology</strong></td><td>Improvement in technology reduces costs</td><td>Technology becomes obsolete or more expensive</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Indirect taxes</strong></td><td>Tax reduced (lowers production cost)</td><td>Tax increased (raises production cost)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Subsidies</strong></td><td>Subsidy granted (reduces effective cost)</td><td>Subsidy removed</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Future price expectations</strong></td><td>Firms expect lower prices — sell now</td><td>Firms expect higher prices — withhold supply</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Prices of related goods (joint supply)</strong></td><td>Price of joint product rises → more of both produced</td><td>Price of joint product falls</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Prices of related goods (competitive supply)</strong></td><td>Price of competing good falls → switch to this good</td><td>Price of competing good rises → switch away</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Number of firms</strong></td><td>More firms enter the market</td><td>Firms exit the market</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout key-term">
      <div class="callout-title">Key terms</div>
      <p><strong>Joint supply:</strong> Two goods produced together from the same process (e.g., beef and leather). A rise in demand for one increases supply of both.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:0.5rem;"><strong>Competitive supply:</strong> Goods that use the same resources to produce — a firm must choose between them (e.g., wheat vs barley on the same land).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Movements Along vs Shifts of the Supply Curve</h2>
    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="content-card">
        <div class="content-card-title">Movement along the curve</div>
        <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Caused by a <strong>change in price</strong> of the good. Movement up the curve = extension in supply. Movement down = contraction in supply.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <div class="content-card-title">Shift of the curve</div>
        <p style="font-size:0.9rem;">Caused by a change in any <strong>non-price determinant</strong>. A rightward shift = increase in supply (more supplied at every price). A leftward shift = decrease in supply.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Law of supply: price up → quantity supplied up (positive relationship)</li>
      <li>Supply curve slopes upward</li>
      <li>Non-price factors shift the curve: factor costs, technology, taxes, subsidies, expectations, number of firms</li>
      <li>Price change → movement along curve</li>
      <li>Non-price change → shift of curve</li>
      <li>HL: diminishing marginal returns → increasing marginal costs → upward slope</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-2">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Practice questions are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions</div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. State the law of supply and explain why the supply curve is upward sloping.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          The law of supply states that, ceteris paribus, as price rises, quantity supplied rises. The supply curve slopes upward because higher prices increase profit margins, making it worthwhile for existing producers to expand output and for new firms to enter the market. At the firm level, producing more involves rising marginal costs (due to diminishing returns), so higher prices are needed to justify additional production.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. A drought destroys a large portion of the wheat harvest. Using a supply diagram, show and explain the effect on the market supply of wheat.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          A drought increases the cost of production and destroys existing output, reducing the ability of producers to supply wheat at every price level. The supply curve shifts to the left (S1 to S2), representing a decrease in supply. At any given price, less wheat is now available. This is a shift of the curve caused by a change in a non-price determinant (costs/availability of the factor land).
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. Explain, using examples, the difference between "joint supply" and "competitive supply."</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <strong>Joint supply</strong> exists when two goods are produced together in the same production process. For example, beef and leather both come from cattle — if more cattle are raised for beef, more leather is also produced as a byproduct. An increase in the price of beef shifts the supply of leather to the right. <strong>Competitive supply</strong> exists when producing more of one good means producing less of another, because they compete for the same limited resources. For example, a farmer with fixed land must choose between growing wheat or barley — if wheat prices rise, the farmer switches land to wheat, reducing the supply of barley.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

